{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}} {{Use Australian English|date=March 2015}} {{Infobox rugby league biography |name = William Brogan |fullname = William Henry Joseph Brogan |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = 1900 |birth_place = |death_date = 1983 |death_place = |height = |weight = |retired = yes |position = |club1 = [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Western Suburbs]] |year1start = 1929 |year1end = 33 |appearances1 = 64 |tries1 = 8 |goals1 = 6 |fieldgoals1 = |points1 = 36 |club2 = Warialda |year2start = |year2end = |appearances2 = |tries2 = |goals2 = |fieldgoals2 = |points2 = |club3 = |year3start = Moree |year3end = |appearances3 = |tries3 = |goals3 = |fieldgoals3 = |points3 = |teamA = [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] |yearAstart = 1929 |yearAend = 32 |appearancesA = 11 |triesA = 3 |goalsA = 1 |fieldgoalsA = |pointsA = 6 |teamB = [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] |yearBstart = 1929 |yearBend = 30 |appearancesB = 3 |triesB = |goalsB = |fieldgoalsB = |pointsB = |teamC = |yearCstart = |yearCend = |appearancesC = |triesC = |goalsC = |fieldgoalsC = |pointsC = |teamD = |yearDstart = |yearDend = |appearancesD = |triesD = |goalsD = |fieldgoalsD = |pointsD = |updated = |source = Whiticker/Hudson. }}'''William Henry Joseph Brogan''' (1900-1983) was an Australian rugby league player of the 1920s and 1930s. He was a [[New South Wales rugby league team|state]] and [[Australia national rugby league team|national]] representative.
Bill Brogan was born at [[West Wyalong, New South Wales]], in 1900. He joined [[Western Suburbs Magpies]] in 1929, and after a stirling season, he was selected on the [[1929/30 Kangaroo Tour]] and played in all three tests against England. Brogan is listed on the ''Australian Players Register'' as Kangaroo No.151.<ref>ARL Annual Report 2005, page 53</ref> Brogan spent five years at Wests between 1929-1933 and won a premiership with them in [[1930 NSWRFL season|1930]]. Bill Brogan also made 11 appearances for [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]]. He retired from Sydney football in 1933 to captain-coach Warialda and Moree Rugby Leagues clubs.<ref>Alan Whiticker/Glen Hudson: Encyclopedia of Rugby League Players. 1995 edition. ({{ISBN|1875169571}})</ref> [[File:Kangaroos 1st Test 1929.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Kangaroos 1st Test 1929.]] Bill Brogan died at [[Earlwood, New South Wales]] on 6 March 1983, aged 83.<ref>Sydney Morning Herald: Death Notice 7/3/1983</ref>
